Equity Research  August 28, 2025

The turnaround's been underway for 3 years & over this period, U- NPAT's fallen \(- 40\%\) . There's no evidence that material improvement is likely in FY26 though the rate cut cycle should mean SSS stop falling. FY26 outlook commentary suggests a weak 1H but better 2H. BAP remains adamant that key Trade segm. is not losing share though GPC results suggest otherwise. We've cut FY26- 27 EPS \(- 14\%\) . Our EBITDA forecasts are \(\sim 6 - 9\%\) below BAP's 2030 flight path.

- FY25 EBITDA A\(247m, - 4\%\) pcp (-1%/- 2% miss vs JEF/Street)- FY25 Segment EBITDA - Trade - 4% miss vs Street; SW +7% beat vs Street; Retail - 2% miss vs Street; NZ - 7% miss vs Street- FY25 U-NPAT A\(80m, - 8\%\) pcp (-1% miss vs JEF/Street)- Final DPS 5.5 vs JEF 8c (miss), Street 5.3 (in-line)

"Continue to capture benefits of FY25 operational improvements and drive further opportunities in FY26 and beyond. Focus the business on sales growth and Gross Profit generation. Segment earnings growth to fund further investment in tech and people capabilities. FY26 NPAT skewed to 2H as benefits from strategic initiatives begin to deliver."

Forecast Changes: With margin pressure across the board, we make - 7% EBITDA cuts to both Specialist Wholesale and Bapcor NZ in FY26/FY27. On higher D&A and net interest expense this sees Group EPS cuts of - 14%/- 13% in FY26/27. FY26 is set to have an NPAT 1H/2H skew of 45/55.

JEF Comment: So much operational and management change underway. It's very difficult to forecast when the benefits will come, what the quantum is (beyond BAP's guided 2030 EBITDA CAGR) and whether there will be further major divestments. Whilst we've put through substantial cuts, we still believe that the core of BAP - Trade, bits of SW and AutoBarn - are significant businesses. An FY26 PE of 15x is not expensive even if you only partially believe in the turnaround. As an aside, massive growth in hybrid powertrains in Aust is not negative.

We historically have viewed BAP as a quality industrial with a solid competitive advantage operating within a highly resilient sector driven mainly by the ageing and growth of the Australian ICE car parc. Industry structure is certainly appealing. However, the last 4 years have seen \(\sim 60\%\) growth in sales base but no growth in NPAT. This is evidence of management and board failures and these shortcomings are in the process of being addressed. Additionally, with de- carbonising pressure growing globally, and with BAP largely driven by the Australian ICE fleet, this long- term factor cannot be ignored.
Risk/Reward - 12 Month View
Base Case, AUD4.55, \(+17\%\)
Our base case PT of \(\mathsf{A}\mathsf{S}4.55\) is premised on a blend of DCF and Aust Auto Comp PE valuations. Our base case multiple valuations ascribe parity to Aust Auto peer group.
Upside Scenario, AUD5.2, \(+34\%\)

Our upside scenario PT of \(\mathsf{A}\mathsf{S}5.20\) is premised on a blend of DCF and Aust Auto Comp PE valuations. Our upside scenario assumes \(2\%\) higher EBITDA margins into perpetuity and a \(0\%\) ascribed multiple premium to Aust peer group.
Downside Scenario, AUD3, \(- 23\%\)

Our downside scenario PT of \(\mathsf{A}\mathsf{S}3.00\) is premised on a blend of DCF and Aust Auto Comp PE valuations. Our downside scenario assumes \(- 3\%\) lower EBITDA margins into perpetuity, 1.2 beta and a \(- 20\%\) ascribed multiple discount to Aust peer group.
Long- term risks remain on ICE products due to adverse emissions regulatory and policy changes around the world.
1) Sustainability targets have not been set by the company.

1) The sector is transitioning from Internal Combustion Engines to Electric Vehicles. This change, though likely to be gradually phased in over ten years or more, will be profound. What are the key commercial implications for BAP from this transition?

2) 2021 saw a dispute between the board and CEO, which ultimately resulted in the long-standing CEO depaing and the stock price declining materially. Little clarity has been provided to the market as to the underlying reasons. This event has seen a loss of confidence in the company's board and governance. What steps has the company taken to strengthen governance and ensure such an event doesn't occur again?

The company is supplied by many component manufacturers based in China, Thailand, and other low labour rate Asian countries. Does the company have a Modern Slavery Policy to ensure these suppliers remunerate employees equitably?
Positive catalysts include: 1) stronger- than- expected volume and margins in FY26; 2) major M&A; 3) more rapid roll- out of own- brands.
Negative catalysts include: 1) Worse sales performance in FY26; 2) Australian government regulatory changes mandating or favouring the take- up of EVs; 3) senior management departures.

BAP's high PE Trade business was the key deta on the result which was disappointing missing JEF - 3% at the EBITDA line. BAP Retai were similarly average results missing JEF EBITDA f/cast's - 7% and - 4% respectively though the consumer environment in both regions were understandably tough so less of a surprise here. Specialist Wholesale was the only segmental EBITDA beat, \(+9\%\) ahead of JEF. This segment suffers from a lack of integration and excessive complexity, so whilst we underestimated this segm. performance, we would prefer to see the Trade & Retail business outperforming instead.

The number of initiatives underway at BAP and the management changes over the past year are somewhat bewildering. We do not necessarily think this is a bad thing. Indeed, BAP's performance has effectively demanded this. However, it does push out the time for turnaround given new starters have to be given time to "get their feet under the desk".

In FY25, there were many key operational changes made across most segments. Not surprisingly, the best performing segment - Trade - had the fewest and was the only segment to see any network growth. The biggest upheaval was in SW and this too is not surprising given the complexity of that segment and the fact that it has seen a lot of M&A and very little integration over the years.

Bapcor Ltd. engages in the sale and distribution of motor vehicle parts and accessories, automotive equipment and services, and motor vehicle servicing. It operates through the following segments: Trade, Bapcor NZ, Specialist Wholesale, and Retail. The Trade segment focuses on automotive aftermarket parts distribution to independent and chain mechanic workshops. The Bapcor NZ segment is involved in Trade and Specialty Wholesale through a variety of businesses including "Brake & Transmission", "Autoling", "HCB Technologies", and "TRS Tyre & Wheel". The Specialist Wholesale segment includes wholesale distribution areas of the organization involved in the specific automotive areas. The Retail segment refers to the retail- focused parts and accessory stores. The company was founded by Garry Johnson and Ron Burgoine in 1971 and is headquartered in Preston, Australia.

We use a blend of two methodologies to derive our BAP target price: discounted cash flow analysis (DCF) and normalised PE multiples. In ascertaining appropriate valuation multiples, we have reviewed listed international automotive parts distribution peers, then used judgment to apply what is considered an appropriate multiple premium to BAP. In terms of risks, on the negative side, BAP may face increased competition from existing competitors (including through downward price pressure), new competitors that enter the industry, vehicle manufacturers, and new technologies or technical advances in vehicles or their parts. In addition, the company called out the risk that new online offerings could negatively impact the company although there is no evidence of this yet. On the positive side, risks include: 1) stronger-than- expected volume and margins in FY25; 2) major M&A; 3) more rapid roll- out of own- brands; and 4) delivery against plan for BTB transformation.
